  "text": "The Boyden chamber is one of the earliest and simplest assays of cell migration [CITATION_1] . It uses an upper and a lower chamber separated by a porous membrane through which cells can migrate (Fig. 1A , Table 1 ). The gradients are formed by placing different concentrations of the chemotactic compound of interest in the upper and lower chambers. A linear gradient is quickly established across the membrane by diffusion (Box 1). Cells respond to the gradient and move from one chamber to the other through pores in the membrane.",
  "correct_citation": {
